In [ ]:
# histogram stretching on the mask
img_mask_stretch_flat = im.histStr(img_mask, 0, 1)
im.show_hist(img_mask_stretch_flat, 'Histogram of stretched mask', 'pixel value', 'number of pixels')

Comparing with previous histogram stretching approach, where entire image was stretched, we don't see a bimodal distribution anymore. In the previous image, the black color on the corners was stretched without any effect because the minimum value of the image and the possible minimum value from the range of values canceled each other out. The presence of this outlier limited the stretching of the range of the intensity values. When we applied histogram stretching on the extracted image (i.e. the fundus part only), we see better use of the possible values, from 0 to 1.

# perform the previous mask detection and histogram stretching, given a file name
# first get a list of files
im_dir = a2.Image_directory('data')
img_file_list = im_dir.get_file_list()
# loop through each image to perform masking and histogram stretching
for i in img_file_list:
    im_proc = a2.Image_process(i)
    orig_img, stretched_img = im_proc.mask_det_hist_str()
    plt.figure(figsize = (15, 5))
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    title_before = i+' before histogram stretching'
    im_proc.show_im(orig_img, title_before, grayscale=1, newFig=False, immediateShow=False)
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    title_after = i+' before histogram stretching'
    im_proc.show_im(stretched_img, title_after, grayscale=1, newFig=False, immediateShow=False)
plt.show()

Bonus Question: Did the histogram stretching procedure does not work perfectly for all three images. What went wrong in one of them? From the above images, it seems to me that histogram stretching has limited advantage when it comes to mostly light or mostly dark image. If we are trying to locate a point on the image where most values are close to the possible intensity range limits, this method will not work well. Since in retina images we want to find the brightest area of the image so that we can estimate the rough location of the optic nerve, this method will not produce the best result for a mostly light image, like we see for 90_left.jpeg. Consequently, if we were trying to find a dark area on the image, histogram stretching would not be best suited for a mostly dark image, as we can see from 71_right.jpeg.
